The study is based on field research in the tropical forest in Puerto Rico, in which American scientists copied a similar survey from 1976. As they write at the beginning of the report, insects are "ten to sixty times less" in the forest today. It is a loss of the entire population, i.e. not the number of species, with researching not only in the insect, but of all artisanal. Due to the extinction of insects, the population of another fauna, which is dependent on insects in the food chain, such as birds, frogs or lizards, is thinning.
The authors of the research put their conclusions in direct connection with climate change. According to them, the average air temperature in the forest has risen by two degrees Celsius in the last thirty years, and warming has become the driving force behind the collapse of the food chain. According to the author's team, the study shows that the impact of climate change on tropical ecosystems may be much greater than previously anticipated.
A large article on the Washington Post was published on Monday, which reports new findings as hyperalarming in the headline. "It's one of the most disturbing articles I've ever read," entomologist David Wagner of the University of Connecticut, whose newspaper quotes as an independent expert, told the newspaper.
