Bloomberg: Venezuela has hidden bitcoins and does not know what to do with them
Venezuela's central bank conducts internal tests to determine whether it can hold cryptocurrencies. It is responding to an instruction from the state-owned company Petróleos de Venezuela (PDVSA), which seeks to send bitcoins and ethers to the central bank, and then the bank pays cryptocurrencies to the suppliers of the oil firm. Employees are also studying a proposal for the central bank to be able to count cryptocurrencies in foreign exchange reserves, which are now close to the low in 30 years. This was reported by Bloomberg, citing information from four sources.
The sanctions imposed by the United States against the authoritarian regime of President Nicolás Maduro have largely cut Venezuela off from the global financial system. This has further deepened the economic crisis in the country. The current crisis is one of the most serious in global comparison, forcing officials to use a mix of different ways to move money. While Maduro’s efforts to launch state cryptocurrency in the world failed, continued efforts to exploit digital currencies show how desperately the government is trying to find ways to circumvent restrictions.
Neither the Venezuelan central bank nor PDVSA have responded to a request for comment.
It is unclear how PDVSA came to its own bitcoins and ethers, nor how much of the value of these currencies it owns. The business has trouble getting payments from customers through conventional channels because large banks are unwilling to trade with entities that are subject to sanctions. Last month, the company received most of the $700 million payment in the Chinese yuan because the parties failed to find financial institutions that would allow the transaction.
PDVSA may not want to sell cryptocurrencies in the open market, because it would require it to register on the stock exchange and undergo an in-depth control, the so-called due diligence. Instead, she wants the central bank to use the cryptocurrency and pay with it to the entities to which the PDVSA owes it. Oil officials believe that the central bank is less exposed to possible obstacles that could arise when paying with cryptocurrencies.
Bitcoins and ethers use a decentralized online ledger known as blockchain to verify and record transactions. In some cases, relatively anonymous transfers are allowed without the need for an intermediary. Fewer banks are involved in digital currencies because of money laundering issues and information about the client that relates to them and complicate compliance.
After the 2018 debacle, cryptocurrencies are experiencing a return to the limelight this year thanks to the expectation of their greater acceptance by the institutions and the plan of Facebook to come up with their own cryptocurrency. Even so, they remain unstable. Bitcoin has fallen by almost 20 percent in the last four days, but has a profit of about 130 percent since the beginning of the year.
