Twenty-six years later, we are more likely to see, from the US to Russia, from Turkey to Poland and from Hungary to Italy, rather illiberal models win, and various forms of nationalism and radicalism thrive. Fukuyama’s current book Identity: The Demand for Dignity and the Politics of Resentment attempts to cope with the onset of these forces. As his interview by George Eaton for the New Statesman shows, many of his former opinions are reconsidered: he argues that the ideas of socialism should be returned to public space, and Marx was right in many ways. At the same time, he insists that his thought development is still in line with the position of the 1990s, and critics have not understood the end of history and the last man correctly.
