Six rare historical manuscripts from the turn of the 14th and 15th centuries, i.e. from the time of Roman and Czech King Wenceslas IV, people in Prague’s Klementinum can see today and Saturday. The National Library has released them from its vaults to commemorate this year's 600th anniversary of Václav's death. This morning, librarians and restorers placed rare originals in the showcases in the Mirror Chapel. Admission to the exhibition is free, it is open both days from 10:00 to 18:00.
The exhibition of documents entitled Ad mandatum domini Regis: From the royal office and the library of Wenceslas IV was prepared by the library together with the National Archives. The National Archives looks at the written heritage from the time of the reign of Wenceslas IV from the point of view of official documents and the National Library from the perspective of literary works, its author Jan Vojtíšek said.
"Visitors can look forward, for example, to the work of agriculture Petra de Crescentiis, which is basically an encyclopedia of agriculture, or a breviary, i.e. a prayer book of one of the Benedictines of the Monastery of the St. Jiří at Prague Castle, from the beginning of the 15 century," he enumerated the reasons why people should look at the exhibition according to him.
The Epistles of Peter of Blois will also be exhibited, where the semi-state of King Henry II of England is depicted in the opening miniature of H (enrico). The author of the decoration is most likely the Master of Samson's History, who, in addition to two volumes of the Bible of Wenceslas IV, also participated in the decoration of a number of other manuscripts. Visitors will also see the Latin adversarial of the tracts of John Wycliff from about 1411 to 1414.
Not a book has been preserved from the Václav IV Library in the Czech Republic. According to experts, this library was one of the most extensive and also the most beautiful book collections in Central Europe at that time, because the young king longed for the construction of a representative library that would match the book collections of his French relatives. However, the library disappeared soon after Václav's death. Apparently, it was stolen or destroyed in the conquest of the castle of the Hussites. Several codes have been saved. Most of them are owned by the Austrian National Library today.
"We have a number of treasures in our collections and I am glad that they are in a state that allows them to be exposed and accessible to the public so-called live and not only in the form of the digital library Manuscriptorium," said Martin Kocanda, director of the National Library.
On Saturday's public holiday, an exhibition entitled What is hidden under the floor, which presents local archaeological discoveries, will be opened in Klementinum for free.
